====Notes====
* {{note|alif|1}} In the beginning of a word, <span style="font-size:140%;">آ</span> ([[Harakat#Madda|alif with madda]]) represents the long vowel {{IPAslink|ɑ}} in words borrowed from other languages (e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;"> آغا </span> – '''ā'''ğā, a title).<ref>[http://qamosona.com/G/index.php/term/,6f57b19b61545aaf9b9ea5adad59.xhtml Pashto-English Dictionary]</ref> In the beginning of a word, the alphabet <span style="font-size:140%;">ا</span> (alif) represents the consonant {{IPAslink|a}}, e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;">اسپه</span> – '''a'''spa, "mare".<ref>[http://qamosona.com/G/index.php/term/,6f57b19b61545aaf9b9ea5b0b05c5e.xhtml Pashto-English Dictionary]</ref> In the middle or end of a word, <span style="font-size:140%;">ا</span> represents the long vowel {{IPA|/ɑ/}} which is following a consonant (e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;">کال</span> – k'''ā'''l, "year"; and <span style="font-size:125%;">نيا</span> – ny'''ā''', "grandmother").<ref>[http://qamosona.com/G/index.php/term/,6f57b19b61545aaf9b9ea5afab5c61ae.xhtml Pashto-English Dictionary]</ref><ref>[http://qamosona.com/G/index.php/term/,6f57b19b61545aaf9b9ea5aeac585db0.xhtml Pashto-English Dictionary]</ref> In the beginning of a word, the alphabet Alif can also be used with a diactric mark [often not written] e.g. <span style="font-size:140%;">اِ</span> (alif with a zer) as in <span style="font-size:125%;">اِسلام</span> – '''I'''slām, "Islam (''the religion'')".<ref>[http://qamosona.com/G/index.php/term/25,11914.xhtml ''mohammedanisme'' in Dutch and Flemish-Pashto Dictionary]</ref>
* {{note|loan|2}} Ten letters, <span style="font-size:140%;">ق ف ع ظ ط ض ص ح ﺫ ث</span>, appear only in loanwords which of Arabic origin through Persian borrowings. Eight of these, <span style="font-size:140%;">ع ظ ط ض ص ح ﺫ ث</span>, represent no additional phonemes of Pashto, and their pronunciation is replaced with other phonemes.
* {{note|h|3}} <span style="font-size:140%;">ح</span> {{IPAslink|h}} tends to be omitted in pronunciation when at the end of a word, e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;">اصلاح</span> is always pronounced as [isˡlɑ].
* {{note|rr|4}} The letter <span style="font-size:140%;">ړ</span> represents {{IPAslink|ɺ̢}} if it is not at the final position of a [[syllable]]; if it is final, it represents {{IPAslink|ɻ}}.
* {{note|f|5}} The phoneme {{IPAslink|f}} <span style="font-size:140%;">ف</span> occurs only in loanwords. It tends to be replaced with {{IPAslink|p}} <span style="font-size:140%;">پ</span>.
* {{note|f|6}} The phoneme {{IPAslink|q}} <span style="font-size:140%;">ق</span> occurs only in loanwords. It tends to be replaced with {{IPAslink|k}} <span style="font-size:140%;">ک</span>.
* {{note|k|7}} It is also common to write the letter <span style="font-size:140%;">ک</span> as <span style="font-size:140%;">ك</span>.
* {{note|g|8}} It is also common to write the letter <span style="font-size:140%;">ګ</span> as <span style="font-size:140%;">گ</span>.
* {{note|j|9}} In informal texts, <span style="font-size:140%;">ی</span> as well as <span style="font-size:140%;">ې</span>, <span style="font-size:140%;">ۍ</span> and <span style="font-size:140%;">ئ</span> are sometimes replaced by the letter <span style="font-size:140%;">ے</span>, especially in [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]. In some official texts, edited till to the middle of the 20th century, the <span style="font-size:140%;">ے</span> corresponds only to <span style="font-size:140%;">ې</span>, while <span style="font-size:140%;">ۍ</span> and <span style="font-size:140%;">ئ</span> (if only the grammatical use of the latter is not lacked) are used as in official typing nowadays.
* {{note|je|10}} <span style="font-size:140%;">ی</span> represents {{IPA|/ai/}} when it is following a consonant (e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;">لرګی</span> – larg'''ay''', "wood"), and represents {{IPA|/j/}} when it is following a vowel (e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;">دوی</span> – du'''y''', "they").
* {{note|y|11}} The letter <span style="font-size:140%;">ئ</span> represents {{IPA|/j/}} after a vowel, e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;">جدائي</span> – judā'''y'''ī, "separation".
* {{note|ye|12}} It is also common to write <span style="font-size:140%;">ﺉ</span> with the hamza over the right side of the letter – <span style="font-size:140%;">ٸ</span>.
* {{note|ə|13}} The letter <span style="font-size:140%;">ۀ</span> is only represented at the end of a word, e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;">تېر'''ۀ'''</span> – ter'''ə''', "sharp". The vowel {{IPA|/ə/}} when present between consonants is unrepresented by the <span style="font-size:140%;">ۀ</span> alphabet, e.g. <span style="font-size:125%;">ننوتل</span>  – n'''ə'''nawat'''ə'''l, "to enter".
* {{note|gh|14}} Pashtuns tend to omit or not pronounce the letter <span style="font-size:140%;">غ</span> and some words, e.g. consider the following words; دغه = دا، دغوی = دوی، دغه هومره = دومره، دغلته = دلته، هغلته = هلته، دغه سی = داسی

====Historical letters now in disuse====
The superscribed element of the letter <span style="font-size:140%;">{{lang|ps|ځ}}</span> in earlier varieties was not hamza-shaped, but was very similar to ''little kāf'' of the letter <span style="font-size:140%;">{{lang|ps|ك}}</span>.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ivanov|first1=Vladimir|last2=Novgorodova|first2=Irina|title=L2/01-316. Arabic Letter Final/Isolated Kaf Sign|url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2001/01316-Kaf-Sign-Proposal.pdf|website=www.unicode.org|publisher=Unicode, Inc.}}</ref> Such shape of the upper element of the letter is hard to find in modern fonts. 

Since the time of [[Pir Roshan|Bayazid Pir Roshan]], <span style="font-size:140%;">{{lang|ps|ڊ}}</span> (dāl with subscript dot) was used for {{IPA|/d͡z/}}, which was still used in the Diwan of Mirza written in 1690 CE,<ref name="khyber">[http://www.khyber.org/publications/026-030/standardpashto.shtml D. N. MacKenzie, "A Standard Pashto",  Khyber.org]</ref> but this sign was later replaced by <span style="font-size:140%;">{{lang|ps|ځ}}</span>.

Another rare glyph for {{IPA|/d͡z/}} is <span style="font-size:140%;">{{lang|ps|ج}}֗</span>, a ج with the same dot above.

